  m0001: {
    id: 'm0001', bookId: 'master', bookLabel: 'Master Index · UX Laws', chapter: 'UX Laws',
    title: 'Parkinson’s Law',
    def: 'Work expands to fill the time available for its completion — give a task a week and it will somehow take a week, even if it could genuinely be done in a day.',
    why: 'This law is the direct justification for timeboxing in design process, and it explains why open-ended deadlines on design deliverables reliably produce more elaborate, slower work than a tightly scoped sprint would, without any real gain in quality.',
    blocks: [
      { t: 'p', text: 'The practical design-process implication is that deliberately shortening the time allotted to a task — a strict one-hour design critique instead of an open-ended half-day, a two-week design sprint instead of an open-ended quarter — tends to produce comparably good or better outcomes, because the artificial scarcity of time forces prioritization that unlimited time never demands. This is the same underlying mechanic behind why the Design Sprint format compresses months of debate into five focused days.' },
      { t: 'ul', items: [
        'Explicit timeboxing (a 90-minute workshop instead of "let\'s take the time we need") tends to produce sharper, more decisive outcomes precisely because the constraint forces prioritization.',
        'Open-ended project timelines invite scope creep — extra polish, extra edge cases, extra debate — that a tighter deadline would have simply forced the team to defer or cut.',
      ]},
    ],
    examples: [
      { label: 'Example · A design review with no time limit', text: 'An unbounded design review meeting reliably runs long and often ends without a clear decision, as attendees feel no urgency to converge. The same review, timeboxed to 30 minutes with an explicit "we decide by the end of this call" framing, tends to reach a clear decision in that same 30 minutes.' },
      { label: 'Example · A five-day design sprint', text: 'A cross-functional team given an open-ended timeline to solve a strategic problem might debate for months. The same team, given a strict five-day Design Sprint structure, reliably converges on a validated direction within the week — the compressed timeline itself is what forces the prioritization.' },
    ],
    mistake: 'Giving a design task an unnecessarily generous, open-ended timeline in the belief that more time reliably produces better craft — in practice it more often just produces more deliberation and lower urgency, not proportionally better outcomes.',
    interview: 'Being able to explain why you deliberately timeboxed a workshop or a critique — citing Parkinson\'s Law by name — demonstrates structured, evidence-aware facilitation judgment.',
    related: [],
  },
