    title: 'Postel’s Law',
    def: 'Also called the Robustness Principle (originally from network engineering): "be liberal in what you accept, and conservative in what you send" — an interface should accept a wide range of reasonable user input, while its own outputs should be precise and predictable.',
    why: 'This principle directly justifies flexible input parsing (accepting many phone-number or date formats) while insisting on strict, consistent output formatting — a common but not universally applied discipline in form design.',
    blocks: [
      { t: 'ul', items: [
        'Be liberal in what you accept — a phone number field should accept spaces, dashes, and parentheses in whatever format the user naturally types, rather than rejecting anything that doesn\'t match one rigid pattern exactly.',
        'Be conservative in what you send — the system\'s own output (a confirmation number, a formatted date) should always be displayed in one single, consistent, predictable format, regardless of how it was originally entered.',
      ]},
      { t: 'p', text: 'Applied to interface design, this principle argues against forcing users to conform to a rigid input format the system could easily normalize itself — accepting "9876543210", "987-654-3210", and "(987) 654-3210" equally and normalizing internally is far more user-respecting than rejecting anything but one exact pattern.' },
    ],
    examples: [
      { label: 'Example · A flexible phone-number field', text: 'A form field that accepts a phone number typed with or without dashes, spaces, or a country code — normalizing it internally to one canonical format — respects Postel\'s Law far better than one that rejects any input not matching an exact regex pattern.' },
      { label: 'Example · Consistent output despite flexible input', text: 'Regardless of how a date was entered (typed, picked from a calendar, pasted from elsewhere), the system should always display it back to the user in one single, consistent format — this is the "conservative in what you send" half of the principle in practice.' },
    ],
    mistake: 'Rejecting reasonable input variations with a rigid, overly strict validation pattern, forcing users to conform exactly to the system\'s preferred format rather than the system doing the work of normalizing flexible input itself.',
