    id: 'm0529', bookId: 'master', bookLabel: 'Master Index · Interaction Design', chapter: 'Interaction Design',
    title: 'Gaze-Based Interaction',
    def: 'A broader category of interactions using eye direction or focus as a meaningful input signal, encompassing eye tracking technology but also simpler, camera-inferred attention signals used for content or interface adaptation.',
    why: 'Gaze signals can inform genuinely useful adaptive behavior (pausing video content when a user looks away) without requiring the full precision of dedicated eye-tracking hardware, making lighter-weight gaze inference a broadly applicable design tool.',
    blocks: [
      { t: 'p', text: 'Effective gaze-based interaction design uses inferred attention as a soft signal informing adaptive behavior (not a hard, binary trigger for consequential actions), and remains genuinely respectful of privacy given the sensitivity of tracking where someone is looking, even approximately.' },
    ],
    examples: [
      { label: 'Example · Gaze inference informing a soft adaptive behavior', text: 'A video player paused automatically when camera-inferred attention detected the user had looked away from the screen for a sustained period, a soft, low-risk adaptive behavior appropriate to the signal\'s inherent imprecision.' },
      { label: 'Example · Gaze inference used for a hard, consequential trigger', text: 'A system used imprecise gaze inference to trigger an irreversible action directly, a poor match between a genuinely noisy signal and a consequential, hard-to-reverse outcome.' },
    ],
    mistake: 'Using imprecise, camera-inferred gaze signals to trigger consequential, hard-to-reverse actions directly — this signal type is better suited to soft, low-risk adaptive behaviors than high-stakes triggers.',
