    title: 'Vertical Integration',
    def: 'A corporate strategy where a company expands its control over multiple stages of its own supply or value chain, either backward toward suppliers or forward toward distribution and customers.',
    why: 'Understanding vertical integration helps a design leader appreciate why a company might suddenly need to design an entirely new type of interface — like an internal supplier-management tool — as a direct consequence of a broader strategic vertical integration decision.',
    blocks: [
      { t: 'p', text: 'Design work following a vertical integration decision often involves entirely new categories of interface the design team hasn\'t built before, requiring genuine new domain research rather than assuming existing design patterns from the company\'s core product will transfer directly to this new context.' },
    ],
    examples: [
      { label: 'Example · Domain-research-grounded vertical integration design', text: 'A team designing a new internal tool following a vertical integration decision conducted genuine domain research into the new operational context, recognizing existing consumer-product design patterns wouldn\'t directly transfer.' },
      { label: 'Example · Pattern-assumption-based vertical integration design', text: 'A team designed a new internal tool following vertical integration by directly reapplying existing consumer product design patterns, missing genuinely different needs specific to the new operational domain.' },
    ],
    mistake: 'Directly reapplying existing consumer-product design patterns to a new tool required by a vertical integration decision — the new operational domain likely has genuinely different needs requiring fresh research.',
